300
00:19:43,530 --> 00:19:45,430
The first computer
you're ever gonna see.

301
00:19:45,597 --> 00:19:46,996
What's the screen for?

302
00:19:47,166 --> 00:19:49,690
<i>I was never good at talking
to people in those days... </i>

303
00:19:49,867 --> 00:19:53,063
<i>... but Steve, he was amazing. </i>

304
00:19:53,236 --> 00:19:57,228
Alexander Graham Bell when he heard his
first ring, that's as revolutionary as this is.

305
00:19:57,406 --> 00:20:01,033
He's talking about the Altair? I never
had a problem till I tried to use it.

306
00:20:01,208 --> 00:20:04,768
<i>All of a sudden we found out what
we wanted to do with our lives. </i>

307
00:20:04,944 --> 00:20:07,343
<i>- It was all we ever wanted. 
- To 30.</i>

308
00:20:07,512 --> 00:20:10,571
Here is the first personal computer
that you're gonna wanna buy.

309
00:20:14,551 --> 00:20:17,747
Man, 50! We sold 50.

310
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:20,911
IBM is gonna be
loading in their pants.

311
00:20:21,089 --> 00:20:23,022
I don't even think
IBM knows who we are.

312
00:20:23,190 --> 00:20:25,555
Good. This is guerrilla warfare.

313
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:28,420
- They're the enemy.
- They are?

314
00:20:28,593 --> 00:20:32,824
I used to think maybe Steve was
born obsessed with wiping out IBM.

315
00:20:32,996 --> 00:20:34,462
And in a way, you could see why.

316
00:20:34,630 --> 00:20:37,154
I mean, in those days,
as far as we were concerned...

317
00:20:37,332 --> 00:20:39,697
...IBM was practically
like the Pentagon.

318
00:20:41,836 --> 00:20:44,565
<i>Here were a bunch of guys
who dressed exactly the same... </i>

319
00:20:44,738 --> 00:20:46,034
<i>... and sang company songs. </i>

320
00:20:54,610 --> 00:20:56,441
<i>I mean, we were
these scruffy crazies... </i>

321
00:20:56,612 --> 00:21:00,774
<i>... messing around with computer stuff
the IBM guys thought was, like, toys. </i>

322
00:21:00,948 --> 00:21:02,778
<i>But what did they know?</i>

323
00:21:09,386 --> 00:21:11,717
- Where's your VW?
- Sold it.

324
00:21:12,088 --> 00:21:16,183
1350 bucks. We're on our way.

325
00:21:16,358 --> 00:21:18,086
- Steve.
- What?

326
00:21:18,259 --> 00:21:21,056
- What's the problem?
- I don't know if I can build these.

327
00:21:21,228 --> 00:21:24,196
Hey, Woz, I assume we're speaking
the same language, right?

328
00:21:24,363 --> 00:21:27,422
Dan, Elizabeth,
I'm not speaking Swahili, am I?

329
00:21:27,732 --> 00:21:29,995
I'm here to inform you
our universe is unfolding...

330
00:21:30,167 --> 00:21:32,192
But I still don't think
I can build them.

331
00:21:32,368 --> 00:21:34,097
I work for Hewlett-Packard sometimes.

332
00:21:34,270 --> 00:21:35,998
- Yeah, and?
- My dad pointed it out...

333
00:21:36,171 --> 00:21:38,365
...they get first chance
in anything I invent.

334
00:21:38,773 --> 00:21:40,673
- What?
- I can't help it.

335
00:21:40,841 --> 00:21:42,740
It's on the paper I signed.

336
00:21:42,909 --> 00:21:46,241
Damn it, Woz!
We get our shot, our destiny...

337
00:21:46,411 --> 00:21:49,072
...and now we gotta turn it
all over to these businessmen?

338
00:22:07,692 --> 00:22:11,353
Steve. It is Steve, isn't it?

339
00:22:12,362 --> 00:22:15,330
Yeah. Steve, you say
that this gadget of yours...

340
00:22:15,497 --> 00:22:17,862
...is for ordinary people.

341
00:22:18,533 --> 00:22:22,468
What on earth would ordinary
people want with computers?

342
00:22:56,558 --> 00:22:58,048
What?

343
00:23:04,329 --> 00:23:06,058
What?

344
00:23:06,598 --> 00:23:08,531
They hated it.

345
00:23:09,533 --> 00:23:11,727
They hated it.

346
00:23:11,901 --> 00:23:13,561
They hated it.

347
00:23:46,490 --> 00:23:48,583
Whenever Steve went
to a bank to get a loan...

348
00:23:48,758 --> 00:23:52,284
...it was like they were Eskimos,
