00:49:09,999 --> 00:49:12,331
It should be taught
in all the history books.

700
00:49:12,501 --> 00:49:15,764
I mean, hung and framed
in the National Gallery or something.

701
00:49:15,936 --> 00:49:18,597
Because this is the instant of creation...

702
00:49:18,771 --> 00:49:22,035
...of one of the greatest fortunes
in the history of the world.

703
00:49:22,207 --> 00:49:27,837
I mean, Bill Gates is the richest guy in the
world because of what started in this room.

704
00:49:28,011 --> 00:49:29,444
You wanna know what else?

705
00:49:29,613 --> 00:49:33,604
It wasn't exactly smoke and mirrors,
but we didn't have anything.

706
00:49:33,781 --> 00:49:37,511
I mean, not a damn thing.

707
00:49:38,018 --> 00:49:40,178
Here we were, this two-bit little outfit...

708
00:49:40,353 --> 00:49:44,311
...telling IBM we had the answer
to their problems.

709
00:49:44,489 --> 00:49:47,252
DOS? The Disk Operating System?

710
00:49:47,424 --> 00:49:51,153
To make all those zillion
IBM computers compute?

711
00:49:51,326 --> 00:49:55,421
We didn't even remotely own
anything like what Bill was selling them.

712
00:49:55,596 --> 00:49:57,927
<i>Nada, zip.</i>

713
00:50:02,968 --> 00:50:05,834
Of course, we don't just
wanna sell it to you outright.

714
00:50:06,003 --> 00:50:07,994
We wanna be able to license it to you.

715
00:50:08,171 --> 00:50:11,503
- You want to retain ownership?
- Right.

716
00:50:12,741 --> 00:50:18,336
Well, the profits are in the computers
themselves, not this software stuff.

717
00:50:21,780 --> 00:50:23,372
No big deal.

718
00:50:24,048 --> 00:50:25,276
Oh, and one other thing.

719
00:50:25,449 --> 00:50:27,609
We have to be able...

720
00:50:27,784 --> 00:50:30,274
...to sell it to other outfits.

721
00:50:32,521 --> 00:50:33,851
But...

722
00:50:34,022 --> 00:50:38,855
...there was just one little problem.

723
00:50:40,159 --> 00:50:43,650
Bill, why did you tell them
we have an operating system?

724
00:50:43,828 --> 00:50:46,455
We don't have a thing to sell them now.
We're dead.

725
00:50:46,630 --> 00:50:50,724
- We're not. You'll give us the miracle, right?
- Oh, yeah, right.

726
00:50:50,899 --> 00:50:54,527
Well, come on. You said you knew a guy
we could buy an operating system from.

727
00:50:54,702 --> 00:50:56,692
I said I sort of know him.

728
00:50:56,870 --> 00:51:00,032
Sort of? You heard me.
Don't tell me "sort of. " I just told IBM.

729
00:51:01,573 --> 00:51:03,472
Sort of.

730
00:51:09,378 --> 00:51:12,039
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

731
00:51:27,490 --> 00:51:30,981
So basically, you're saying
you wanna buy my operating system.

732
00:51:31,160 --> 00:51:32,387
Yeah.

733
00:51:37,364 --> 00:51:38,591
Why?

734
00:51:42,734 --> 00:51:48,671
You know, I don't know. We just think we
might be able to mess with it and resell it.

735
00:51:48,838 --> 00:51:50,065
Who to?

736
00:51:50,238 --> 00:51:53,001
We have a few customers, you know,
we're sort of talking to.

737
00:51:53,174 --> 00:51:55,698
Some of them don't want it known
what we're doing.

738
00:51:55,875 --> 00:51:59,275
So they made us sign
a secrecy agreement.

739
00:52:02,480 --> 00:52:05,277
- And you're offering us...?
- Fifty thousand.

740
00:52:05,449 --> 00:52:08,212
- Dollars?
- Dollars.

741
00:52:15,456 --> 00:52:16,683
You worried?

742
00:52:16,856 --> 00:52:19,915
Oh, no. Only my whole life hangs
in the balance. Me, worried? No.

743
00:52:21,326 --> 00:52:23,190
We got IBM.

744
00:52:23,361 --> 00:52:25,851
IBM. I mean, come to think of it...

745
00:52:26,029 --> 00:52:29,520
...why would IBM wanna make a deal
with a bunch of bozos like us?

746
00:52:29,698 --> 00:52:31,688
Because they're successful, Ballmer.

747
00:52:31,866 --> 00:52:35,460
Success is a menace. It fools smart people
into thinking they can't lose.

748
00:52:47,243 --> 00:52:48,642
So?

749
00:52:51,947 --> 00:52:54,073
So, you mute moron?

750
00:53:06,256 --> 00:53:09,122
<i>Can you hear it? The sound of money?</i>

751
00:53:10,692 --> 00:53:14,149
<i>The roar of money. It was like everywhere
you turned, money poured down. </i>

752
00:53:14,328 --> 00:53:16,261
<i>Millions and more millions. </i>

753
00:53:16,429 --> 00:53:20,888
<i>All because we bought that guy's
operating system for a measly 50,000 bucks. </i>

754
00:53:21,066 --> 00:53:26,559
<i>That fueled a worldwide explosion of wealth
unlike anything in the history of man. </i>

755
00:53:26,736 --> 00:53:28,999
<i>But you know something?</i>

756
00:53:29,171 --> 00:53:34,266
<i>Having money and being cool
are not necessarily the same thing. </i>

757
00:53:34,441 --> 00:53:36,738
- Hi, I'm Bill Gates...
- Hey.

758
00:53:37,676 --> 00:53:39,575
What in the...?

759
00:53:41,179 --> 00:53:42,475
Hi.

760
00:53:43,047 --> 00:53:45,480
You know, you should really watch
where you're going.

761
00:53:46,049 --> 00:53:48,017
You must have really great bandwidth.

762
00:53:48,184 --> 00:53:51,118
- Excuse me?
- What are you doing later?

763
00:53:56,923 --> 00:53:58,913
Who is that jerk?

764
00:54:02,360 --> 00:54:04,088
Way to go, hotshot.

765
00:54:07,530 --> 00:54:10,692
When Paul and I were at Lakeside,
we were in 10th grade together...

766
00:54:10,865 --> 00:54:14,197
...we rigged a computer so we could
get classes with all the best girls.

767
00:54:14,368 --> 00:54:16,301
Obviously, it's been downhill since then.

768
00:54:16,469 --> 00:54:20,097
You should walk around with your bankbook
hanging from a chain on your belt.

769
00:54:20,272 --> 00:54:23,798
Or maybe you ought to stop yelling
in front of your employees.

770
00:54:23,973 --> 00:54:26,998
Girls don't like yelling. They like cool.

771
00:54:27,176 --> 00:54:29,804
Oh, really, Ballmer?
How do you get to be cool?

772
00:54:30,511 --> 00:54:33,479
<i>I don't know. You saw
Saturday Night Fever. Travolta's cool.</i>

773
00:55:02,166 --> 00:55:07,830
I'd like to welcome all of you to the new
headquarters and home of Apple Computers.

774
00:55:08,003 --> 00:55:10,197
<i>All of a sudden, Steve was a huge star. </i>

775
00:55:10,371 --> 00:55:13,134
<i>The kind where people practically
hang on your every word... </i>

776
00:55:13,307 --> 00:55:15,706
<i>... like they're excited
just to be around you. </i>

777
00:55:15,875 --> 00:55:19,810
Thank you very much
for joining us today on this lovely day...

778
00:55:19,978 --> 00:55:22,605
...and helping us stop the gossip rumors
in their tracks.

779
00:55:22,780 --> 00:55:24,644
Without further ado,
the rumors are true.

780
00:55:24,814 --> 00:55:27,304
Ladies and gentlemen,
our new president, John Sculley.

781
00:55:33,353 --> 00:55:37,254
To tell you the truth, I was perfectly happy
to be president of Pepsi-Cola...

782
00:55:37,423 --> 00:55:40,914
...until Steve Jobs came to recruit me
and said:

783
00:55:41,091 --> 00:55:43,889
"Do you wanna sell sugared water
for the rest of your life...

784
00:55:44,060 --> 00:55:45,652
...or do you wanna make history?"

785
00:55:47,162 --> 00:55:48,823
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

786
00:55:48,997 --> 00:55:51,021
- I know.
- Yeah, operator.

787
00:55:51,198 --> 00:55:54,223
- I need information for Oregon.
- Okay, give me a minute.

788
00:55:58,903 --> 00:56:02,099
Steve, I gotta talk. I don't know how
to act in situations like this.

789
00:56:02,272 --> 00:56:04,967
- In a minute.
- I mean, Steve, that stock-offering thing?

790
00:56:05,141 --> 00:56:06,369
A hundred million dollars?

791
00:56:06,542 --> 00:56:08,702
- What do you do with $ 116 million?
- In a minute.

792
00:56:08,877 --> 00:56:12,835
I don't think rich, okay? I know a lot of
people think rich, but I don't think rich.

793
00:56:13,013 --> 00:56:17,038
I mean, maybe you learn it, but, jeez,
$ 100 million. That's a lot of learning to do.

794
00:56:17,215 --> 00:56:20,206
I hardly ever had enough for lunch
before all this.

795
00:56:20,985 --> 00:56:23,384
We should have given stock
to the other guys, Steve.

796
00:56:23,553 --> 00:56:26,214
Like Dan?
Dan's been with us since we started...

797
00:56:26,388 --> 00:56:29,083
...and you didn't set aside
any stock for him.

798
00:56:31,225 --> 00:56:32,885
Steve.

799
00:56:33,693 --> 00:56:36,490
- I'm gonna give Dan some of my stock.
- Yeah, is Arlene there?

800
00:56:36,662 --> 00:56:38,356
We gotta do the right thing.

801
00:56:38,930 --> 00:56:41,193
<i>Arlene? Okay, fine. 
Let's talk about this baby. </i>

802
00:56:41,365 --> 00:56:44,595
Steve, why do you care
what I call the baby?

803
00:56:44,767 --> 00:56:47,826
Because I don't want
the baby named Rainbow.

804
00:56:48,003 --> 00:56:52,029
Or Orisha or Ravi Shankar
or any other name like that.

805
00:56:52,705 --> 00:56:55,138
Steve, not right now, okay?

806
00:56:55,307 --> 00:56:58,969
<i>Well, when the hell is a good time to call?
Because every time I try...</i>

807
00:57:01,811 --> 00:57:03,608
Steve.

808
00:57:52,078 --> 00:57:54,012
- Do you want me to take that?
- Thank you.

809
00:57:54,180 --> 00:57:55,874
You're welcome.

810
00:58:20,130 --> 00:58:21,596
Hi.

811
00:58:22,198 --> 00:58:23,688
Hi.

812
00:58:26,535 --> 00:58:29,503
So I just came by to make sure
everything's okay.

813
00:58:30,870 --> 00:58:33,531
- Everything okay?
- Thank you.

814
00:58:45,447 --> 00:58:47,540
And to...

815
00:58:47,716 --> 00:58:50,979
...make sure that you're not
gonna name it some weird name.

816
00:58:54,620 --> 00:58:57,679
What's wrong with naming her Orisha?

817
00:58:58,623 --> 00:59:00,681
Or Sunshine or Purity?

818
00:59:02,325 --> 00:59:04,815
A kid's got enough problems
in this world...

819
00:59:04,994 --> 00:59:07,018
...not knowing where it belongs.

820
00:59:07,195 --> 00:59:08,718
A name can label a kid.

821
00:59:09,796 --> 00:59:11,354
Make it...

822
00:59:11,530 --> 00:59:13,896
It can make it an outsider.

823
00:59:14,633 --> 00:59:16,157
Not "it. "

824
00:59:16,334 --> 00:59:17,561
Her.

825
00:59:18,802 --> 00:59:20,360
Her.

826
00:59:31,845 --> 00:59:33,402
Lisa.

827
00:59:37,315 --> 00:59:38,975
Okay.

828
00:59:39,449 --> 00:59:40,939
Okay.

829
00:59:43,886 --> 00:59:45,819
She's your daughter too.

830
00:59:47,855 --> 00:59:51,085
Arlene, let's not go through that again.

831
01:00:04,266 --> 01:00:07,257
You don't just live in life.

832
01:00:07,435 --> 01:00:12,097
You change it, you shape it,
you make your mark upon it.

833
01:00:12,772 --> 01:00:15,365
And that's what, get used to the name...

834
01:00:16,074 --> 01:00:18,940
...Lisa is gonna do.

835
01:00:19,109 --> 01:00:20,336
Yeah!

836
01:00:20,510 --> 01:00:23,910
<i>You know, that computer was
the first big new project we had at Apple. </i>

837
01:00:24,079 --> 01:00:28,276
<i>And some people are still wondering
why Steve insisted on that name. </i>

838
01:00:29,316 --> 01:00:31,284
You wanna call a computer Lisa?

839
01:00:32,484 --> 01:00:34,475
Isn't that your baby's...?

840
01:00:34,652 --> 01:00:36,381
I mean...

841
01:00:36,554 --> 01:00:41,285
What's her name? Arlene.
Isn't that Arlene's baby's name?

842
01:00:41,457 --> 01:00:44,186
Other guys here
have daughters named Lisa.

843
01:00:44,359 --> 01:00:48,727
Steve, you got a baby up there
you don't even wanna talk about.

844
01:00:49,595 --> 01:00:53,724
- I mean, it looks sort of...
- Sort of what?

845
01:01:03,005 --> 01:01:06,872
We have to think of ourselves as artists.

846
01:01:08,175 --> 01:01:10,438
It's like Picasso said:

847
01:01:10,609 --> 01:01:14,305
Good artists copy. Great artists steal.

848
01:01:16,447 --> 01:01:19,279
<i>This is who we wanted
to steal from. Xerox. </i>

849
01:01:19,449 --> 01:01:21,973
<i>They were secretly developing
all this amazing stuff... </i>

850
01:01:22,150 --> 01:01:26,017
<i>... like the mouse and the graphics on the
screen instead of just a bunch of numbers. </i>

851
01:01:26,187 --> 01:01:29,019
<i>But when those California engineers
had to go to New York... </i>

852
01:01:29,189 --> 01:01:31,782
<i>... and present all this neat stuff
to the Xerox brass... </i>

853
01:01:31,957 --> 01:01:35,448
<i>... those executives didn't begin
to understand what they were looking at. </i>

854
01:01:35,626 --> 01:01:41,221
<i>Never mind a mouse. It was like someone
dumped a dead rat on the boardroom table. </i>

855
01:01:48,868 --> 01:01:50,665
A mouse.

856
01:01:54,939 --> 01:01:58,999
You want Xerox to consider
something called a mouse?

857
01:02:05,146 --> 01:02:07,477
<i>See, this is where Steve was a genius... </i>

858
01:02:07,647 --> 01:02:11,241
<i>... because he persuaded Xerox
into showing us all this incredible stuff... </i>

859
01:02:11,417 --> 01:02:13,213
<i>... their California guys had developed. </i>

860
01:02:13,385 --> 01:02:16,012
<i>I tell you, it was making their people
absolutely nuts. </i>

861
01:02:17,421 --> 01:02:19,149
Oh, God.

862
01:02:22,758 --> 01:02:24,691
Let's go.

863
01:02:25,826 --> 01:02:28,419
<i>You know, I felt like
one of the Mongol hordes... </i>

864
01:02:28,595 --> 01:02:32,325
<i>... coming to loot and plunder
a bunch of defenseless villagers. </i>

865
01:02:34,332 --> 01:02:37,095
No, no. This is insane.

866
01:02:37,267 --> 01:02:39,393
We'd just be handing him everything.

867
01:02:39,568 --> 01:02:44,732
We created the mouse and all the rest of it,
and now these idiots in New York...

868
01:02:44,906 --> 01:02:46,930
...want to show it all to Steve Jobs.

869
01:02:47,107 --> 01:02:48,471
I won't do it.

870
01:02:48,641 --> 01:02:51,632
Hi. I'm Steve Jobs.

871
01:02:54,378 --> 01:02:57,778
I need you to answer some other questions
about the stuff you've invented.

872
01:02:57,947 --> 01:02:59,937
The graphic interface?

873
01:03:02,418 --> 01:03:04,214
It's not going to hurt.

874
01:03:04,719 --> 01:03:06,151
That's what you think.

875
01:03:08,221 --> 01:03:10,711
- What do you want to know?
- How does it...?

876
01:03:10,890 --> 01:03:13,585
What is your base length?
Is it integer, or is it compound?

877
01:03:13,758 --> 01:03:16,282
Does your operating system
convert to executable codes?

878
01:03:16,460 --> 01:03:19,895
- I got it. I got it, Steve-O. I got it, Steve-O.
- What is the middle...?

879
01:03:25,065 --> 01:03:27,658
It's pretty neat, right?

880
01:03:27,834 --> 01:03:30,427
Click, you're there.

881
01:03:30,769 --> 01:03:32,827
Click, you're somewhere else.

882
01:03:33,004 --> 01:03:37,064
This graphic interface stuff was like
a miracle back then, and we got it.

883
01:03:37,240 --> 01:03:41,402
Steve got it, from Xerox, who just
turned it all over for us to fool with.

884
01:03:41,576 --> 01:03:45,033
Like rich people giving junky old stuff
to the Salvation Army...

885
01:03:45,212 --> 01:03:48,510
...only the junk turns out
to be a Rembrandt.

886
01:03:48,681 --> 01:03:52,241
About $ 100 billion head start
on everyone else.

887
01:03:52,417 --> 01:03:56,045
Apple was making tons of money.
It was great.

888
01:03:56,219 --> 01:04:00,917
And of course, I sort of lost my mind.
I mean, it was all fun and games.

889
01:04:01,089 --> 01:04:03,682
I started buying really expensive toys.

890
01:04:05,559 --> 01:04:07,925
<i>It was me with my own plane. </i>

891
01:04:08,093 --> 01:04:11,619
<i>Only problem was, maybe I wasn't
as good a pilot as I thought I was. </i>

892
01:04:11,796 --> 01:04:15,026
<i>I mean, it's one thing
when computers crash, but planes?</i>

893
01:04:15,199 --> 01:04:16,427
<i>You don't want to know. </i>

894
01:04:23,771 --> 01:04:26,204
Hey, Steve. Are you just getting here?

895
01:04:26,372 --> 01:04:28,602
No, I was just outside
talking to the doctor.

896
01:04:28,774 --> 01:04:31,174
You don't remember us
talking 10 minutes ago?

897
01:04:31,343 --> 01:04:33,173
- We talked?
- Yeah.

898
01:04:33,344 --> 01:04:35,504
Hey, my hard disk crashed.

899
01:04:38,380 --> 01:04:41,041
A computer guy with memory problems.

900
01:04:42,984 --> 01:04:44,883
Oh, man.

901
01:04:45,052 --> 01:04:48,248
It's the weirdest thing.
You know there's a part of your life there...

902
01:04:48,421 --> 01:04:50,388
...only you don't know about it.

903
01:04:50,555 --> 01:04:52,920
It makes you crazy.

904
01:05:07,333 --> 01:05:09,096
Hey.

905
01:05:10,268 --> 01:05:12,532
Hey!

906
01:05:14,638 --> 01:05:16,264
Paul.

907
01:05:16,439 --> 01:05:18,930
Simonyi, get Matthews.

908
01:05:19,108 --> 01:05:21,041
Ballmer, get in here.

909
01:05:24,011 --> 01:05:27,036
- What is it?
- This is seriously crummy.

910
01:05:27,213 --> 01:05:29,772
Apple's new computer, Lisa? We're dead.

911
01:05:29,948 --> 01:05:31,505
Oh, yeah, I've already seen one.

912
01:05:31,682 --> 01:05:33,945
The graphics and the operating system
they have...

913
01:05:34,117 --> 01:05:36,949
...they make what we're selling IBM
look a decade out-of-date.

914
01:05:37,119 --> 01:05:39,246
- I want it.
- What do you mean, you want it?

915
01:05:39,421 --> 01:05:44,755
- It's Apple's. We can't just go and steal it.
- You're not listening to me. I want it.

916
01:05:44,925 --> 01:05:51,419
<i>Final call for TWA flight 2684
to San Jose. Final call. </i>

917
01:05:52,630 --> 01:05:56,121
- Fifty bucks he misses the flight.
- You're on.

918
01:05:56,299 --> 01:05:58,266
It wouldn't hurt to buy a car radio, Bill.

919
01:05:58,433 --> 01:06:00,662
- I can't pick up the radio...
- One traffic report.

920
01:06:00,835 --> 01:06:03,326
- Hold on.
- Sir, we're on this plane.

921
01:06:03,504 --> 01:06:06,336
I'm sorry. Your plane is on the runway.

922
01:06:06,506 --> 01:06:08,564
Ma'am, what kind of service
is this today?

923
01:06:08,741 --> 01:06:12,675
I'm sorry, sir. There's nothing that can bring
that plane back to the gate.

924
01:06:12,843 --> 01:06:16,505
Yes, there is. Willpower. I'm going to will
that that plane be turned around.

925
01:06:16,679 --> 01:06:18,771
- Oh, really?
- Really, sir.

926
01:06:18,947 --> 01:06:22,746
Are you aware that today in my briefcase
are computer language codes?

927
01:06:22,917 --> 01:06:25,510
- Do you know what they do, sir?
- I'm afraid I don't.

928
01:06:25,685 --> 01:06:28,744
They protect against viruses.
You're aware of viruses, I presume?

929
01:06:28,921 --> 01:06:33,288
- Sir, I do go to doctors.
- No, sir, computer viruses.

930
01:06:33,456 --> 01:06:35,856
Oh, yeah, I just read an article
about those things.

931
01:06:36,026 --> 01:06:39,051
- They can wipe out a whole computer.
- A whole system of computers.

932
01:06:39,227 --> 01:06:42,423
Like the one behind your terminal there,
like the one in the plane...

933
01:06:42,596 --> 01:06:46,793
...like the one on all planes in the airlines,
like the one in the control tower, sir.

934
01:06:46,966 --> 01:06:50,264
I ask you, are you prepared
to take responsibility for your actions...

935
01:06:50,435 --> 01:06:53,460
...if I don't get this information
on that plane?

936
01:06:55,138 --> 01:06:59,506
Jeez, his reputation for inconveniencing
the rest of the world is intact.

937
01:06:59,675 --> 01:07:01,369
He actually missed a flight.

938
01:07:01,542 --> 01:07:05,307
<i>This is your captain speaking. We have
to return to the gate for a few minutes. </i>

939
01:07:05,478 --> 01:07:07,775
<i>Nothing critical. </i>

940
01:07:13,216 --> 01:07:18,083
<i>- Attention, please, flight... 
- Your tickets, please.</i>

941
01:07:18,253 --> 01:07:22,518
- You have the tickets, right?
- No, I gave them to you.

942
01:07:23,690 --> 01:07:26,022
Bill, in the car.

943
01:07:42,669 --> 01:07:45,831
Wow. These guys must be
50 times bigger than we are.

944
01:07:46,005 --> 01:07:48,996
Good artists copy. Great artists steal.

945
01:07:49,174 --> 01:07:52,665
- Oh, yeah? Who said that?
- Some artist. I think it was Van Gogh.

946
01:07:53,977 --> 01:07:56,843
Hey, check it out.

947
01:07:58,347 --> 01:08:03,339
Aye, matey. It wouldn't be time
to rape and pillage, would it?

948
01:08:11,421 --> 01:08:14,355
You sure it's okay
to let these Microsoft guys in here?

949
01:08:14,657 --> 01:08:17,591
We have culture. They don't.

950
01:08:17,926 --> 01:08:21,019
No taste. No original thinking.

951
01:08:21,662 --> 01:08:23,959
But they can be useful to us.

952
01:08:24,597 --> 01:08:27,360
Time for the dog and pony show.

953
01:08:36,405 --> 01:08:38,770
Welcome to Apple.

954
01:08:49,014 --> 01:08:50,708
Bill.

955
01:08:51,949 --> 01:08:53,848
Nice to see you. Thanks for coming.
Steve.

956
01:08:54,017 --> 01:08:56,917
- How you doing, Steve?
- Glad you're here. Paul. Hi, Steve Jobs.

957
01:08:57,085 --> 01:08:59,644
- Hi. Charles Simonyi.
- Come on in. Let me introduce you.

958
01:08:59,820 --> 01:09:02,413
This is Gilmore.
He's one of our top programmers.

959
01:09:02,956 --> 01:09:05,549
And he's a loyal man.
Well, to do this, you need loyalty.

960
01:09:06,425 --> 01:09:09,621
- Total loyalty. Isn't that right?
- That's the plan, Steve.

961
01:09:10,394 --> 01:09:14,830
This way. The Macintosh team.
It's more like a family.

962
01:09:14,997 --> 01:09:17,829
Everybody else is an outsider.

963
01:09:17,999 --> 01:09:21,195
- What's with the pirate stuff?
- What do I always tell you?

964
01:09:21,669 --> 01:09:23,727
Better to be a pirate than join the Navy.

965
01:09:23,903 --> 01:09:27,065
- You a pirate?
- Oh, yeah. Yeah, absolutely, Steve.

966
01:09:27,639 --> 01:09:29,401
I've been up for 52 hours straight.

967
01:09:31,042 --> 01:09:32,269
Loyalty.

968
01:09:40,981 --> 01:09:43,005
I'm gonna show you the future.

969
01:09:43,182 --> 01:09:46,810
It's top-secret. It's still about...

970
01:09:46,985 --> 01:09:49,782
...a year away from introduction.

971
01:09:50,287 --> 01:09:53,153
The ultimate, insanely great...

972
01:09:54,724 --> 01:09:56,918
...fusion of art and science.

973
01:09:58,526 --> 01:10:02,655
- It's called the Macintosh.
- This is definitely not the Lisa.

974
01:10:02,829 --> 01:10:05,058
That's a graphic user interface.

975
01:10:05,230 --> 01:10:08,960
I don't understand. How does a computer
handle the mouse-cursor display?

976
01:10:09,133 --> 01:10:11,123
Hardware's got nothing to do
with the mouse.

977
01:10:11,301 --> 01:10:13,598
- It's all in the software.
- Enough.

978
01:10:13,769 --> 01:10:15,963
Sorry, Steve.

979
01:10:16,371 --> 01:10:19,828
There's no point in torturing our guests...

980
01:10:20,340 --> 01:10:22,807
...with what they can't have.

981
01:10:30,980 --> 01:10:33,777
You're vulnerable in spreadsheets,
you know, Steve.

982
01:10:33,949 --> 01:10:36,213
We can help you.

983
01:10:38,052 --> 01:10:41,282
Ninety hours a week. Like the T-shirt?
I'm gonna give it to my people.

984
01:10:43,723 --> 01:10:46,384
Some of them work even more
than 90 hours a week.

985
01:10:46,558 --> 01:10:49,458
We have Multiplan running on
dozens of different platforms.

986
01:10:49,626 --> 01:10:51,786
No one can match us.

987
01:10:52,595 --> 01:10:54,960
You can't just have employees anymore.

988
01:10:55,130 --> 01:10:56,757
It's great.

989
01:10:57,732 --> 01:10:59,791
No, they gotta be into a crusade.

990
01:10:59,967 --> 01:11:05,665
It's like art, science, religion,
all rolled into one.

991
01:11:05,838 --> 01:11:09,897
We have multi-tool interface.
It can be redesigned for the Mac.

992
01:11:10,073 --> 01:11:13,735
Redesigned. Redesigned.

993
01:11:14,376 --> 01:11:16,570
We're artists here.

994
01:11:16,745 --> 01:11:19,372
A place where raw sand
comes in one end...

995
01:11:19,546 --> 01:11:23,675
...and goes out the other. Silicon art.

996
01:11:26,318 --> 01:11:30,514
You know, IBM, they're gonna want
all our stuff.

997
01:11:31,254 --> 01:11:32,653
IBM?

998
01:11:34,490 --> 01:11:37,617
IBM, they're history.

999
01:11:37,792 --> 01:11:43,228
I mean, they're 1950s, they're ice America,
a bloated enemy in a crumbling castle.

1000
01:11:43,395 --> 01:11:46,192
- And we're storming it.
- I know IBM is the enemy, Steve.

1001
01:11:46,364 --> 01:11:48,558
But we can help you.

1002
01:11:49,099 --> 01:11:51,032
You don't have to worry about IBM.

1003
01:11:51,768 --> 01:11:53,701
Yeah?

1004
01:11:53,869 --> 01:11:55,894
So why you even working with them?

1005
01:11:56,570 --> 01:11:59,232
I'd much rather work with you.

1006
01:12:09,146 --> 01:12:11,011
We're in.

1007
01:12:11,580 --> 01:12:13,741
- We're doing work for Apple.
- You're kidding me.

1008
01:12:13,916 --> 01:12:16,850
They're sending us three prototypes
of the computer we just saw.

1009
01:12:17,018 --> 01:12:18,507
- The Macintosh.
- For God sakes.

1010
01:12:18,685 --> 01:12:22,450
There's a pirate flag flying above our heads,
and he's giving us the crown jewel?

1011
01:12:22,622 --> 01:12:24,248
Who the hell's the pirate here?

1012
01:12:24,422 --> 01:12:26,753
He sees what he believes,
not the other way around.

1013
01:12:26,924 --> 01:12:28,721
We're not his worst problem.

1014
01:12:28,893 --> 01:12:31,656
If he's not careful,
he's gonna wreck the place.

1015
01:12:32,661 --> 01:12:34,891
- Macintosh! Macintosh!
- Macintosh rules!

1016
01:12:35,062 --> 01:12:37,996
- Apple II's the best!
- Mac's the best!

1017
01:12:38,165 --> 01:12:41,429
<i>Even when I got my memory back,
it was never the same for me. </i>

1018
01:12:41,600 --> 01:12:43,568
<i>I couldn't believe
how it had all changed. </i>

1019
01:12:43,736 --> 01:12:45,862
<i>Apple was tearing itself to pieces. </i>

1020
01:12:46,471 --> 01:12:49,030
<i>Steve had turned it into two camps:</i>

1021
01:12:49,206 --> 01:12:53,732
<i>His new Macintosh group
against everyone else in the company. </i>

1022
01:12:57,878 --> 01:13:00,573
Steve, what the hell is this?

1023
01:13:01,114 --> 01:13:04,912
It's like a family. Things get messy.

1024
01:13:05,316 --> 01:13:06,681
I don't understand this.

1025
01:13:06,851 --> 01:13:10,013
You got the Mac people
against the Apple II people?

1026
01:13:10,187 --> 01:13:12,279
- They're beating each other up.
- Amazing, huh?

1027
01:13:12,454 --> 01:13:15,889
People wanna be shaped, molded.

1028
01:13:16,057 --> 01:13:18,786
But if you asked any of them,
any of them, they'd deny it.

1029
01:13:19,393 --> 01:13:23,725
I don't wanna shape anybody, Steve.
This isn't fun anymore.

1030
01:13:23,895 --> 01:13:27,455
Maybe fun is just fragments of existence
with better packaging.

1031
01:13:29,365 --> 01:13:30,832
I don't make jokes anymore.

1032
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:34,832
I told you a long time ago, I like jokes.

1033
01:13:35,002 --> 01:13:40,267
Steve! Goodbye. I'm quitting Apple.

1034
01:13:41,540 --> 01:13:46,407
- Well, that's a joke, right?
- No. I'm going back to college.

1035
01:13:46,577 --> 01:13:52,377
Woz. Hey, what are you doing?
I don't think it's such a good idea.

1036
01:13:52,547 --> 01:13:56,448
All I'm doing now is being a brake pedal
for you as you're heading for the wall.

1037
01:13:59,052 --> 01:14:01,281
Woz!

1038
01:14:30,739 --> 01:14:33,673
- I ask you for brilliance?
- Steve.

1039
01:14:33,841 --> 01:14:38,800
I've asked you for genius,
and you're giving me this?

1040
01:14:40,079 --> 01:14:42,013
Steve, please.

1041
01:14:52,254 --> 01:14:54,983
Oh, no, Steve, not again.

1042
01:14:55,155 --> 01:14:59,113
It's 3 a. m., okay? I don't have the energy
to defend an unfinished design.

1043
01:14:59,292 --> 01:15:02,818
That's because there's nothing to defend.

1044
01:15:02,995 --> 01:15:07,327
I want beauty, not incompetence.

1045
01:15:08,064 --> 01:15:10,122
Are you listening to me?

1046
01:15:10,866 --> 01:15:12,765
- Are you listening...?
- Yes, I'm listening!

1047
01:15:12,934 --> 01:15:15,027
I am so sick of your abusiveness.

1048
01:15:16,303 --> 01:15:19,396
That's all you know.
Tearing people down, throwing tantrums.

1049
01:15:19,572 --> 01:15:24,974
- You miserable son of a bitch.
- What are you doing? Come on, back off.

1050
01:15:39,318 --> 01:15:42,343
<i>I know we've been in a battle... </i>

1051
01:15:42,520 --> 01:15:46,046
...and like all battles,
we've had our casualties along the way.

1052
01:15:46,857 --> 01:15:48,551
But today's about celebrating.

1053
01:15:50,526 --> 01:15:52,049
The Macintosh.

1054
01:15:58,631 --> 01:16:00,598
It's time for a christening...

1055
01:16:02,434 --> 01:16:05,197
...of our little Macintosh.

1056
01:16:05,369 --> 01:16:07,268
Our baby.

1057
01:16:17,077 --> 01:16:19,772
- Congratulations.
- Congratulations.

1058
01:16:21,513 --> 01:16:24,345
Real artists ship.

1059
01:16:24,782 --> 01:16:28,273
In this company, in Apple,
in the entire business...

1060
01:16:28,451 --> 01:16:33,182
...we, you, the Macintosh team,
are the only true artists.

1061
01:16:33,354 --> 01:16:36,049
You can forget Apple, forget Lisa.

1062
01:16:36,222 --> 01:16:39,748
It's only us. The Macintosh team.

1063
01:16:39,925 --> 01:16:42,757
We have been chosen to seize history.

1064
01:16:44,161 --> 01:16:49,826
But first, carpe diem, seize the day.
It's your time to party, people.

1065
01:16:52,167 --> 01:16:54,157
Hey, John.

1066
01:16:54,835 --> 01:16:56,392
You hear what I heard in there?

1067
01:17:24,488 --> 01:17:28,389
- Hey, man, what'd you say about Steve?
- I'm sick of his crap.

1068
01:17:28,557 --> 01:17:30,422
- What'd you say, man?
- You heard me.

1069
01:17:30,592 --> 01:17:32,786
You wanna talk like that about Steve?

1070
01:17:32,960 --> 01:17:35,621
You wanna talk like that about the guy
who feeds you, man?

1071
01:17:35,795 --> 01:17:39,696
- The guy who feeds you?
- Come on. Break it up.

1072
01:17:39,865 --> 01:17:41,661
Come on.

1073
01:17:43,134 --> 01:17:45,567
- Hey, hey, guys.
- Somebody pull him off.

1074
01:17:46,003 --> 01:17:48,835
- Never like this at Pepsi-Cola.
- Knock it off.

1075
01:17:49,304 --> 01:17:52,102
You wanna sell sugar water
the rest of your life?

1076
01:18:05,482 --> 01:18:07,711
Steve, I'm worried.

1077
01:18:10,184 --> 01:18:11,617
Yeah?

1078
01:18:11,786 --> 01:18:14,481
Yeah, about what's happening.

1079
01:18:14,921 --> 01:18:19,549
All the, you know, "them versus us" stuff.
Macintosh versus Apple II.

1080
01:18:19,724 --> 01:18:23,181
You don't understand, John.
People need a cause.

1081
01:18:23,360 --> 01:18:26,726
We missed Vietnam. This is our Vietnam.

1082
01:18:27,963 --> 01:18:31,625
- It's tearing the company apart.
- Creation is messy.

1083
01:18:31,799 --> 01:18:34,596
You want genius, you get madness.
Two sides of the same coin.

1084
01:18:34,768 --> 01:18:36,860
You knew that when I brought you in.

1085
01:18:37,036 --> 01:18:39,596
Steve, if you can't trust me,
then God help you.

1086
01:18:39,771 --> 01:18:42,762
I didn't mention anything
about trust, John.

1087
01:18:46,409 --> 01:18:47,706
There's another problem.

1088
01:18:50,311 --> 01:18:52,870
- It's Arlene and the baby.
- That's my business.

1089
01:18:53,047 --> 01:18:57,107
<i>No, not anymore.
TIME magazine is doing another story.</i>

1090
01:18:57,283 --> 01:18:59,546
You don't need the bad press.
Neither do we.

1091
01:18:59,718 --> 01:19:02,652
- Child's not mine.
- Steve, come on. You took a paternity test.

1092
01:19:03,486 --> 01:19:05,920
She is yours.
It's right there in the results.

1093
01:19:06,089 --> 01:19:10,581
- Paternity tests are a joke.
- She's asking for $20,000.

1094
01:19:10,758 --> 01:19:13,157
- Total, nothing more.
- Blackmail.

1095
01:19:13,326 --> 01:19:16,294
Steve, you can afford the money.
Give her what she's asking for.

1096
01:19:16,462 --> 01:19:19,191
- You should give her more.
- It's not about the damn money.

1097
01:19:19,531 --> 01:19:21,725
Well, what is it, then?

1098
01:19:21,899 --> 01:19:23,992
I don't know.

1099
01:20:15,968 --> 01:20:18,697
Mommy, there's a man here.

1100
01:20:35,714 --> 01:20:38,910
It's been what, a year?

1101
01:20:41,918 --> 01:20:45,876
- Yeah, I've been busy.
- I'm sure.

1102
01:20:48,089 --> 01:20:51,990
- Why'd you come?
- I don't know.

1103
01:20:54,026 --> 01:20:55,926
She's looking really good.

1104
01:21:02,265 --> 01:21:04,665
You should have come to see her.

1105
01:21:04,834 --> 01:21:08,893
- You could have brought her by.
- Oh, Steve.

1106
01:21:11,605 --> 01:21:13,539
Here.

1107
01:21:23,746 --> 01:21:25,679
Thank you.

1108
01:21:26,281 --> 01:21:28,272
Thank you, Lisa.

1109
01:22:04,540 --> 01:22:07,940
- Steve Jobs is killing us. Ballmer!
- Yeah?

1110
01:22:08,109 --> 01:22:10,077
This stuff is crummy. It's totally crummy.

1111
01:22:10,243 --> 01:22:13,075
- Windows was supposed to ship last year.
- We're ready for you.

1112
01:22:13,245 --> 01:22:15,713
Why do I have to do this?
I have work. This is stupid.

1113
01:22:15,881 --> 01:22:18,007
<i>It's good PR.
It's for The Wall Street Journal.</i>

1114
01:22:18,183 --> 01:22:20,912
- I don't need PR.
- Can you stand a little to the left?

1115
01:22:21,084 --> 01:22:24,519
The hole in that sweater of your shirt.
Turn all the way to the right.

1116
01:22:24,687 --> 01:22:26,278
What am I, a trained seal?

1117
01:22:26,454 --> 01:22:29,616
- Lf Apple can do this, why can't we?
- What do you want us to do?

1118
01:22:29,790 --> 01:22:31,916
- Whatever you have to.
- Meaning what, Bill?

1119
01:22:32,091 --> 01:22:34,217
Meaning ship Windows
before the snow falls.

1120
01:22:34,393 --> 01:22:36,986
- This is Seattle. It doesn't snow here.
- Whatever, Steve.

1121
01:22:37,161 --> 01:22:39,629
Mr. Gates, I think you should
take off your sweater...

1122
01:22:39,796 --> 01:22:41,923
...because it clashes
with the background.

1123
01:22:42,098 --> 01:22:44,258
The green and blue,
it's just not in these days.

1124
01:22:44,433 --> 01:22:46,423
It's not in at all.

1125
01:22:46,601 --> 01:22:50,036
Sweat stains. This is awful.

1126
01:22:56,308 --> 01:22:59,640
- I'd like to get back to work...
- I know, we're almost ready.

1127
01:22:59,810 --> 01:23:06,111
Okay, and three, two, one.
Smile, please.

1128
01:23:06,981 --> 01:23:09,108
Urgent, Mr. Gates.

1129
01:23:09,283 --> 01:23:12,046
Thank you. What's next?

1130
01:23:13,485 --> 01:23:15,316
Steve Jobs.

1131
01:23:15,653 --> 01:23:18,416
"Mr. Jobs demands you be
in his office tonight. "

1132
01:23:20,090 --> 01:23:22,080
He's getting paranoid
over what we're doing.

1133
01:23:22,525 --> 01:23:23,856
Maybe he should be.

1134
01:23:25,126 --> 01:23:27,151
Not at the pace you're going.

1135
01:23:27,328 --> 01:23:29,319
I think I had a date tonight with Ann.

1136
01:23:29,496 --> 01:23:31,520
- I thought she was away on business.
- She is.

1137
01:23:31,698 --> 01:23:33,255
Then how can you have a date?

1138
01:23:33,432 --> 01:23:37,231
Well, I go to a movie here, and then
she goes to the same movie in Denver...

1139
01:23:37,401 --> 01:23:40,028
...and then we talk on the phone
about it afterwards.

1140
01:23:40,203 --> 01:23:44,366
Jeez, Bill, I hate to see what happens
when you two have sex.

1141
01:24:27,701 --> 01:24:30,692
You're stealing from us!

1142
01:24:33,338 --> 01:24:36,670
Steve, we're not stealing from you.
So don't tell me that.

1143
01:24:38,009 --> 01:24:39,669
What the hell are you doing, then?

1144
01:24:39,843 --> 01:24:44,301
What is this that I keep hearing
about you developing this...?

1145
01:24:44,479 --> 01:24:47,073
What do you call it? Windows?

1146
01:24:47,247 --> 01:24:49,579
To compete with us?

1147
01:24:52,151 --> 01:24:56,518
- I'm not doing anything against you, Steve.
- Don't give me that crap!

1148
01:24:56,687 --> 01:24:59,985
You're pirating the software
off our Mac prototypes!

1149
01:25:00,156 --> 01:25:01,817
I trusted you.

1150
01:25:02,391 --> 01:25:06,827
If you wanna know everything
we're working on, I'll show you.

1151
01:25:14,399 --> 01:25:15,764
<i>The weird thing was... </i>

1152
01:25:15,933 --> 01:25:19,629
<i>... Steve Jobs was the one guy
Bill would never yell at. It was the opposite. </i>

1153
01:25:19,803 --> 01:25:23,032
<i>Steve would order Bill to fly down there
and then blow up at him... </i>

1154
01:25:23,204 --> 01:25:26,900
<i>... but Bill, he would just wait it out,
convince Steve that we were no threat... </i>

1155
01:25:27,074 --> 01:25:30,668
<i>... that this Windows stuff was just
that much more smoke and mirrors... </i>

1156
01:25:30,843 --> 01:25:33,106
<i>... and a few hours later,
everything was fine. </i>

1157
01:25:33,278 --> 01:25:35,336
<i>I'm telling you, Bill's a genius at it. </i>

1158
01:25:36,614 --> 01:25:38,877
And that's all you're working on?

1159
01:25:39,349 --> 01:25:40,577
Of course.

1160
01:25:41,483 --> 01:25:43,780
- Yeah?
- You know what else?

1161
01:25:44,085 --> 01:25:47,679
Did you read what I said in that
newspaper story on us two days ago?

1162
01:25:48,121 --> 01:25:51,146
- No. What'd you say?
- I said when your Macintosh comes out...

1163
01:25:51,324 --> 01:25:54,190
...that'd be the only computer
I'd want to buy my mom.

1164
01:25:54,559 --> 01:25:56,788
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

1165
01:25:57,294 --> 01:25:59,853
Your mom, huh?

1166
01:26:00,029 --> 01:26:04,464
- It's like we're one big family, you know?
- Family?

1167
01:26:07,300 --> 01:26:08,528
You know that.

1168
01:26:12,905 --> 01:26:14,963
Family.

1169
01:26:16,540 --> 01:26:18,531
<i>Steve, Steve, Steve, Steve!</i>

1170
01:26:32,217 --> 01:26:33,741
Tell me something.

1171
01:26:33,919 --> 01:26:37,080
When did this stop being a business
and start being a religion?

1172
01:26:37,253 --> 01:26:38,652
Thank you for your work.

1173
01:26:38,822 --> 01:26:43,689
And remember, what we will do
in the next year...

1174
01:26:43,858 --> 01:26:46,883
...will change the way people think...

1175
01:26:47,060 --> 01:26:49,357
...and communicate.

1176
01:26:51,930 --> 01:26:53,761
Hey.

1177
01:26:53,932 --> 01:26:55,592
- Hey.
- So enjoy the revolution...

1178
01:26:55,766 --> 01:26:59,223
...which we have all created and watch...

1179
01:26:59,402 --> 01:27:01,266
You know, Steve thinks IBM's the enemy.

1180
01:27:01,436 --> 01:27:02,767
- Unfolds in front of us.

1181
01:27:02,938 --> 01:27:05,201
He doesn't get it.

1182
01:27:05,373 --> 01:27:07,067
You guys are.

1183
01:27:10,142 --> 01:27:12,201
What are you talking about?

1184
01:27:12,378 --> 01:27:15,107
Copies of your Windows
just started surfacing here.

1185
01:27:15,279 --> 01:27:16,768
You took our stuff, Bill.

1186
01:27:16,947 --> 01:27:20,347
You took our stuff, you fooled with it,
and you called it your own.

1187
01:27:22,584 --> 01:27:25,780
You always insult your guests like this?

1188
01:27:26,520 --> 01:27:28,680
Make no mistake.

1189
01:27:28,855 --> 01:27:32,654
We are all one big family.

1190
01:27:33,624 --> 01:27:36,751
And part of it
are our friends at Microsoft.

1191
01:27:41,397 --> 01:27:43,489
Bill?

1192
01:27:48,634 --> 01:27:51,101
Ladies and gentlemen, Bill Gates.

1193
01:27:55,439 --> 01:27:58,601
Finally, I wanna show you a preview...

1194
01:27:58,775 --> 01:28:02,437
...of the most amazing 60 seconds of film
you'll ever see.

1195
01:28:02,611 --> 01:28:04,840
And we're showing it only once...

1196
01:28:05,012 --> 01:28:06,501
...during the Super Bowl.

1197
01:28:06,679 --> 01:28:09,875
So watch and see how we handle IBM.

1198
01:28:10,382 --> 01:28:12,975
I mean Big Brother.

1199
01:28:15,452 --> 01:28:19,012
<i>See, that commercial was interesting
in a lot of ways... </i>

1200
01:28:19,188 --> 01:28:22,156
<i>... because when we're at
this big hoopla at Apple... </i>

1201
01:28:22,323 --> 01:28:26,053
<i>... and their engineers are unpacking
all these Japanese computers... </i>

1202
01:28:26,226 --> 01:28:28,750
<i>... with the first copies
of our stuff, Windows... </i>

1203
01:28:28,928 --> 01:28:32,192
<i>... that looks a lot like their stuff... </i>

1204
01:28:32,364 --> 01:28:34,354
<i>I mean, if I had to pick a moment... </i>

1205
01:28:44,405 --> 01:28:46,133
Hey...

1206
01:28:46,306 --> 01:28:48,967
...I'm getting
some pretty weird vibes here.

1207
01:28:49,141 --> 01:28:51,005
Sure we should stay around?

1208
01:28:51,776 --> 01:28:56,235
Sometimes you deal them.
Sometimes you fold them.

1209
01:28:57,980 --> 01:29:00,447
Now's not the time to fold.

1210
01:29:01,950 --> 01:29:05,509
<i>We shall prevail. </i>

1211
01:29:10,756 --> 01:29:13,690
I obviously made a mistake.

1212
01:29:16,259 --> 01:29:17,987
I made a mistake.

1213
01:29:19,395 --> 01:29:21,487
I trusted.

1214
01:29:22,430 --> 01:29:24,693
I believed.

1215
01:29:26,165 --> 01:29:28,429
Family.

1216
01:29:31,069 --> 01:29:34,731
Maybe a Mafia family.
You turn your back, and you get whacked.

1217
01:29:34,904 --> 01:29:39,237
Our guys come back from Japan
with this NEC...

1218
01:29:40,275 --> 01:29:44,835
...and it's loaded with Microsoft programs.
Your Microsoft programs.

1219
01:29:45,011 --> 01:29:47,672
They're almost identical to ours.

1220
01:29:50,849 --> 01:29:53,578
There may be some similarities, Steve.

1221
01:29:56,619 --> 01:29:58,280
Similarities?

1222
01:30:01,689 --> 01:30:04,055
Similarities?

1223
01:30:06,292 --> 01:30:09,192
- Try theft.
- Steve, all cars have steering wheels...

1224
01:30:09,361 --> 01:30:12,761
...but no one tries to claim
that the steering wheel was their invention.

1225
01:30:12,930 --> 01:30:17,024
- We have a contract, you and I.
- Well, you should read it more carefully.

1226
01:30:17,199 --> 01:30:19,030
What is this?

1227
01:30:19,501 --> 01:30:21,901
This is like doing business with...

1228
01:30:22,070 --> 01:30:23,331
...like, a praying mantis.

1229
01:30:23,504 --> 01:30:26,563
You get seduced
and then eaten alive afterwards.

1230
01:30:26,939 --> 01:30:29,065
Get real, will you?

1231
01:30:30,742 --> 01:30:34,938
You and I are both like guys
that have this rich neighbor...

1232
01:30:35,111 --> 01:30:37,203
...Xerox...

1233
01:30:37,379 --> 01:30:39,677
...that left the door open all the time.

1234
01:30:39,848 --> 01:30:42,714
And you go sneaking in
to steal the TV set.

1235
01:30:43,116 --> 01:30:47,415
Only when you get there,
you realize that I got there first.

1236
01:30:47,586 --> 01:30:49,951
I got the loot, Steve!

1237
01:30:50,722 --> 01:30:52,484
And you're yelling?

1238
01:30:52,656 --> 01:30:55,283
"That's not fair.

1239
01:30:55,458 --> 01:30:58,551
I wanted to try to steal it first. "

1240
01:31:04,197 --> 01:31:06,324
You're too late.

1241
01:31:12,802 --> 01:31:15,168
We're better than you are.

1242
01:31:19,874 --> 01:31:24,037
- We have better stuff.
- You don't get it, Steve.

1243
01:31:25,111 --> 01:31:27,704
That doesn't matter.

1244
01:31:46,058 --> 01:31:49,788
<i>You know, like a lot of things,
there always seems to be one last time. </i>

1245
01:31:49,961 --> 01:31:52,190
<i>For us, it was when we all
came together again... </i>

1246
01:31:52,362 --> 01:31:55,091
<i>... for this big party
Steve threw for his 30th birthday. </i>

1247
01:31:55,264 --> 01:31:57,288
<i>It was just one of those things. </i>

1248
01:31:57,465 --> 01:32:00,262
<i>You know, where you try really hard
to make something work... </i>

1249
01:32:00,434 --> 01:32:02,732
<i>... but somehow it just doesn't. </i>

1250
01:32:02,903 --> 01:32:06,030
<i>And maybe you should have known it
all along. </i>

1251
01:32:10,007 --> 01:32:13,533
- Is that really Ella Fitzgerald?
- I have absolutely no idea.

1252
01:32:16,812 --> 01:32:18,711
You hear the kind of food
they're serving?

1253
01:32:18,880 --> 01:32:21,473
- Salmon mousse, goat's cheese.
- I can't eat that stuff.

1254
01:32:21,648 --> 01:32:24,878
- Why don't we go to Denny's?
- Is that Joan Baez with him?

1255
01:32:25,051 --> 01:32:26,847
Wait, wait. Who's Joan Baez?

1256
01:32:28,086 --> 01:32:30,212
- Hi.
- John.

1257
01:32:36,658 --> 01:32:38,989
I need to talk to you. It's important.

1258
01:32:39,160 --> 01:32:41,458
Okay, John. Excuse me.

1259
01:32:46,532 --> 01:32:49,591
We've got a problem.
We've been asked to make a toast to Steve.

1260
01:32:49,767 --> 01:32:54,168
Me? Toast Steve? No way, man.
Not after what's happened. No way.

1261
01:32:54,337 --> 01:32:58,295
Oh, John, don't look at me. L...
Mike, you do it.

1262
01:32:58,473 --> 01:33:02,067
After the past few months?
I don't think so.

1263
01:33:02,675 --> 01:33:05,541
John, you're the one.

1264
01:33:05,711 --> 01:33:09,669
- No. Not now. Absolutely no way.
- Why not?

1265
01:33:10,047 --> 01:33:13,015
- Look, Steve thinks I'm his...
- He thinks you're what?

1266
01:33:23,289 --> 01:33:25,917
Ladies and gentlemen, a toast.

1267
01:33:26,224 --> 01:33:28,249
To a remarkable man.

1268
01:33:28,426 --> 01:33:30,256
A man who brought me
to this company...

1269
01:33:30,761 --> 01:33:33,991
...without whom none of this tonight
would ever have happened.

1270
01:33:34,163 --> 01:33:38,757
Steve Jobs, truly a guiding light.
A man who sees the future.

1271
01:33:38,933 --> 01:33:40,161
- Hear, hear!
- Steve.

1272
01:33:40,334 --> 01:33:41,630
Happy birthday!

1273
01:33:47,905 --> 01:33:51,362
It's weird, but sometimes you find things
that are more important to you...

1274
01:33:51,541 --> 01:33:55,374
...than the things you think are important.
You know what I mean?

1275
01:33:55,544 --> 01:33:58,376
Maybe it's just getting older.

1276
01:34:00,147 --> 01:34:04,344
Okay, guys. Let's see how we did.

1277
01:34:05,717 --> 01:34:06,945
That's a good one.

1278
01:34:18,826 --> 01:34:20,383
It's true.

1279
01:34:21,728 --> 01:34:25,719
We're learning about the size of the sun
versus the size of the Earth.

1280
01:34:38,039 --> 01:34:39,472
<i>Hi, Steve. </i>

1281
01:34:39,640 --> 01:34:43,404
<i>I think it's gonna be really interesting,
I mean, you and me together. </i>

1282
01:34:43,809 --> 01:34:45,640
Yeah.

1283
01:34:47,612 --> 01:34:49,602
It is.

1284
01:34:59,600 --> 01:35:02,399
Ripped by:
SkyFury

